Week 3 PwnDriveA Academy

🔍 Phase 1: Reconnaissance & Enumeration
Network Scanning
I initiated the engagement with an Nmap scan to identify open ports and services.

Command:

Bash
nmap -sC -sV -Pn -vv 10.150.150.11
Findings:

Operating System: Windows Server 2008 R2 Enterprise SP1.

Web Services: Port 80 (HTTP) and Port 443 (HTTPS) are active.

Database: Port 3306 (MySQL) and Port 1433 (MSSQL).

Remote Management: Port 3389 (RDP) is open.

SMB: Port 445 is open with Message Signing Disabled, which is a significant security risk.

Directory Brute-Forcing
To find hidden paths, I used Gobuster with a common wordlist.

Command:

Bash
gobuster dir -u http://10.150.150.11/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt
Key Discoveries:

/admin (Status: 301)

/upload (Status: 301)

/vendor (Status: 301)

🛠️ Phase 2: Vulnerability Discovery
Directory Listing Enabled
Upon navigating to the discovered directories, I found that Directory Listing was enabled on the Apache server. This allowed me to view the underlying file structure of the application without any authentication.

/admin/: Contained critical PHP files: addedituser.php, deleteuser.php, and manageusers.php.

/upload/: Contained user-specific subdirectories, potentially exposing sensitive files.

🚀 Phase 3: Exploitation & Gaining Access
Broken Access Control
The application failed to implement proper session validation on the administrative pages. By directly navigating to http://10.150.150.11/admin/manageusers.php, I was granted access to the user management dashboard without logging in.

Account Creation
Using the unprotected addedituser.php page, I was able to:

Create a new user.

Assign the admin role to the account.

I successfully created an account named testuser1 with administrative privileges, as confirmed in the Manage Users table.
